0. Getting started

Install and load the statnet and Bergm packages:

devtools::install_github("acaimo/Bergm")
install.packages("statnet", repos = "http://cran.r-project.org")
library(statnet)
library(Bergm)

1. Network Data

Let’s load the gangs network data (Criminal network of 67 gang members in Italy) and plot the graph:

load(url("http://acaimo.github.io/Bergm/network_data/gangs.Rdata"))

set.seed(27)
CS <- colorspace::rainbow_hcl(10)
VA <- get.vertex.attribute(y, "Nationality")
plot(y, vertex.col = CS[VA], vertex.cex = 2, main = "Italian gang members")
legend("topleft", 
       pt.bg  = CS[unique(VA)], 
       pt.cex = 1.2,
       pch    = 21, 
       legend = unique(VA), 
       title  = 'Nationality')

model <- y ~ edges +                       # density
             nodematch('Nationality') +    # nationality-based homophily
             gwesp(0.5, fixed = TRUE) +    # transitivity
             gwdegree(0.5, fixed = TRUE)   # popularity
summary(model)
                edges nodematch.Nationality       gwesp.fixed.0.5 
            122.00000              52.00000             112.08972 
      gwdeg.fixed.0.5 
             87.28569

3. Parameter estimation

Let’s estimate the parameter posterior distribution using the approximate exchange algorithm (~2.5 minutes):

# Specify a prior distribution: 
prior.mean <- c(-4, 1, 1, 1)
prior.sigma <- diag(3, 4, 4)   

parpost <- bergm(model,
                 prior.mean  = prior.mean,
                 prior.sigma = prior.sigma,
                 burn.in     = 250,
                 main.iters  = 2000,
                 aux.iters   = 10000, 
                 nchains     = 6, 
                 gamma       = 0.4)

bergm.output(parpost)

Let’s estimate the parameter posterior distribution using pseudo-posterior calibration approach (~ 1.6 minutes):

parpost2 <- calibrate.bergm(model,
                            prior.mean  = prior.mean,
                            prior.sigma = prior.sigma,
                            iters       = 100,
                            aux.iters   = 10000,
                            noisy.nsim  = 1000,  
                            noisy.thin  = 1000,
                            burnin      = 200,
                            mcmc        = 10000,
                            tunePL      = 1.5)
bergm.output(parpost2)

4. Model assessment

Bayesian goodness of fit diagnostics:

bgof(parpost,  # or parpost2
     aux.iters = 10000,
     n.deg     = 14,
     n.dist    = 15,
     n.esp     = 9)

5. Model selection

Let’s estimate the model evidence (marginal likelihood) using the Chib and Jeliazkov’s method:

# Estimate the transformation parameters for adjusting the pseudolikelihood:
info.adjustPL <- adjustPL(model,
                          aux.iters  = 10000, 
                          noisy.nsim = 100,
                          noisy.thin = 1000,
                          ladder     = 50,   
                          estimate   = "MLE",
                          control    = control.ergm(MCMC.samplesize = 2000))
                                                
# MCMC sampling and evidence estimation:
evidence.est <- evidence_CJ(model,
                            prior.mean = prior.mean,  
                            prior.sigma = prior.sigma,
                            nits          = 30000,
                            burnin        = 5000,
                            thin          = 1,
                            num.samples   = 25000,
                            tunePL        = 1.5,
                            info.adjustPL = info.adjustPL)   
# MCMC diagnostics and posterior summaries:
bergm.output(evidence.est)
